Not an answer but to give you an insight for (GNU) `sed` flags.

`g` flag is for global, replace all matches.

    $ echo barbarbar.etc | sed &#39;s/bar/foo/g&#39;
    foofoofoo.etc

    $ echo barbarbar.etc | sed &#39;s/bar/foo/&#39;
    foobarbar.etc        

    $ echo barbarbar.etc | sed &#39;s/bar/foo/1&#39;
    foobarbar.etc
    
    $ echo barbarbar.etc | sed &#39;s/bar/foo/2&#39;
    barfoobar.etc
    
    $ echo barbarbar.etc | sed &#39;s/bar/foo/3&#39;
    barbarfoo.etc

    $ echo barbarbar.etc | sed -E &#39;s/bar(.etc)$/foo\1/&#39;
    barbarfoo.etc

`$` here is the anchor for the line end, not needed for the input above but for another input it will only match instance at the line end..

    $ echo barbarbar.etc bar.etc| sed -E &#39;s/bar(.etc)$/foo\1/&#39;
    barbarbar.etc foo.etc

