You could use the [`Enabled` property](https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/api/system.windows.forms.control.enabled) to decide which `Button`s are on and which `Button`s are off.

IF you only need one `Button` active at a time, a simple way to approach this might be to add a few fields to your `Form1` class.

* A `System.Collections.Generic.List&lt;Button&gt;` to store all the buttons that you create inside of `Form1.GenerateButton`. We can call this `_buttons`, for example.
* A `Button` to store the currently selected button. We can call this `_enabledButton`, for example.
* A `Random` to generate random numbers so you can select a button at random. We can call this `_rng`, for example.

Inside of `GenerateButton`, make sure you set `button.Enabled = false`, then also add `button` to the `_buttons` field.

Then add a method to `Form1`, `ActivateRandomButton` for example, that does something like this...

```lang-csharp
private void ActivateRandomButton()
{
   if (_enabledButton != null)
   {
      // If one of the buttons is already enabled, disable it.
      _enabledButton.Enabled = false;
   }
   
   // Randomly select a button that you&#39;ve created and enable it.
   _enabledButton = _buttons[_rng.Next(0, _buttons.Count)];
   _enabledButton.Enabled = true;
}
```
Now after you&#39;ve generated all your `Button`s, you can call `ActivateRandomButton` to turn one of them &quot;On&quot;. You&#39;ll probably eventually add a `Timer` and you can call `ActivateRandomButton` in the `Tick` event.

Do be aware that this is a pretty simplistic approach. It has some problems, for example there will always be one and only one button active at a time. It&#39;s been a long time since I&#39;ve played a game of Whack-a-Mole, but I feel like it&#39;s possible for there to be multiple moles &quot;active&quot; at a time, or even zero moles &quot;active&quot; at a time. Hopefully though, this answer will give you something to start with and build on.

