It seems to be an issue that the DateTime constructor allows invalid ranges: [DateTime.parse should throw an error on invalid date...][1]

Here is a workaround: [How to check if a given Date exists in DART?][2]

You could use it like this:

    bool isValidDate(String input) {
      try {
        final date = DateTime.parse(input);
        final originalFormatString = toOriginalFormatString(date);
        return input == originalFormatString;
      } catch(e) {
        return false;
      }
    }
    
    String toOriginalFormatString(DateTime dateTime) {
      final y = dateTime.year.toString().padLeft(4, &#39;0&#39;);
      final m = dateTime.month.toString().padLeft(2, &#39;0&#39;);
      final d = dateTime.day.toString().padLeft(2, &#39;0&#39;);
      return &quot;$y$m$d&quot;;
    }



  [1]: https://github.com/dart-lang/sdk/issues/11189
  [2]: https://stackoverflow.com/questions/57080005/how-to-check-if-a-given-date-exists-in-dart

